<p class="EnTeteTranscription">McKenzie, James. Some Account of the King's Posts, the Labrador Coast, and the Island of Anticosti by an Indian Trader Residing there Several Years with a Description of the Natives and the Journal of a trip through those Countries in 1808 by the Same Person. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0017</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">King of forty leagues of this coast<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They keep aloof from every other trader<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At their factory where they have erected some elegant building and have a preacher of the Gospel they exchange their commodities with the Eskimaux for Oil Bears Martens &amp; foxes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The distance of this settlement from Quebec is reckoned five hundred leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Country of which I have been drawing the limits is perhaps the part the least favoured by nature in point of climate and soil of the habitable globe<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Man was placed here to exercise his carnivorous appetite only by preying upon the inferior animals around him &#8211; for the soil, composed of moss sand and rock, is too sterile and the climate too cold to produce a substitute for satisfying the cravings of hunger<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  And often does he poor miserable sinner' retire to his hard cold bed without a supper &#8211; and leave it next <span class="DelHand-author">day</span> <span class="AddHand-author">morning</span> without a prospect of procuring for himself and family a breakfast a dinner or any of the other common necessaries of life<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Very few sights I believe can</p>
